      </svg>
      <span class="theme-toggle__thumb" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    </button>
    <main>
      <header class="hero">
        <figure class="hero__photo">
          <Picture
            src={headshot}
            alt="Chuck Reynolds"
            formats={['avif', 'webp']}
            widths={[180, 220, 360, 440]}
            sizes="(min-width: 640px) 220px, 180px"
            loading="eager"
            fetchpriority="high"
          />
        </figure>
        <div class="hero__intro">
          <h1>Chuck Reynolds</h1>
          <p class="tagline">
            AI training data &amp; enterprise API platforms. Developer experience.
            Twenty-five years of making the web actually work.
          </p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <p>
        Hi, I'm Chuck. I'm a <strong>Staff Product Manager, Growth</strong> at
        <a href="https://enterprise.wikimedia.com" rel="me">Wikimedia Enterprise</a>,
        the commercial API platform for Wikipedia, Wikidata, and the rest of the Wikimedia
        projects. Top AI labs and search engines use it two ways: as training data, and as
        live retrieval and grounding at inference. Hundreds of languages, tens of millions
        of articles, one of the largest open knowledge graphs on the internet, and a
        real-time firehose of every edit as it happens.
      </p>

      <p>
        The work I'm best at is <strong>developer experience</strong> and the data
        plumbing underneath it. CLI tooling, API specs and docs, and pipelines that turn
        messy structure into something usable on day one.
      </p>

      <p>
        I build with AI as much as I build for it. Good tooling takes the ceiling off what
        someone can do, developer or not, and that's the part I care about.
      </p>

      <p>
        Twenty-five years got me here. Software engineering throughout, applied to
        websites, ecommerce, marketing applications, and predictive analytics at
        <strong>Levers</strong>: ML for revenue outcomes, back when we just called it
        modeling. Years of it inside <strong>CBS Interactive / ViacomCBS</strong> (later
        <strong>Red Ventures</strong>) as a Senior Technical SEO Analyst across CNET,
        ZDNet, Gamespot, TechRepublic, MetaCritic and others, at a scale where mistakes
        are expensive.
      </p>

      <p>
        Two decades of how information gets structured, ranked, retrieved, and served.
        That turns out to be the same problem AI is solving now.
      </p>

      <h2>What I'm building</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="https://enterprise.wikimedia.com" rel="me"><strong>Wikimedia Enterprise</strong></a>:
          training-data and retrieval APIs for Wikipedia and sibling projects.
          Free tier exists; go play.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://github.com/chuckreynolds" rel="me"><strong>Open source odds and ends</strong></a>:
          social image size references, helpers for running Claude more safely,
          and whatever else I needed badly enough to build.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://vuurr.com" rel="me"><strong>Vuurr</strong></a>:
          Partner since 2011. Digital intelligence firm: custom web apps,
          technical audits, complex campaigns. Past and current clients include GitHub,
          ASU, MIT Sloan, Supercell, Twilio, Parse (Meta), Cox, Keap, Mattermark.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://orbithull.com" rel="me"><strong>OrbitHull</strong></a>:
          modular cargo containers for orbital tasking. (Yes, really.)
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://rynoweb.com" rel="me"><strong>Rynoweb</strong></a>:
          web tech consultancy I've been running since 2001.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://upchuck.us" rel="me"><strong>UpChuck</strong></a>:
          blog-shaped container for the thinking.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Previously</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Levers</strong>: the predictive modeling shop mentioned above. 2nd place at Hollywood Hackathon 2013 applying the same math to IMDB box-office prediction. Retired.</li>
        <li><strong>TWIMLbin</strong>: acquired by Twilio.</li>
        <li><strong>Betwext</strong>: the first SMS marketing platform built on Twilio. Sold, and still running.</li>
        <li>Organized the first two <strong>WordCamp Phoenix</strong> conferences (2009, 2011). Helped init and grow <strong>Gangplank</strong> a collaborative coworking space. Pitched in helping and/or organizing AZ Entrepreneurship Conference, PodCampAZ, Ignite Phoenix, and other local tech events (tweetups! early days were fun).</li>
        <li><strong>BS, Computer Information Technology</strong>, Arizona State University (2000).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Talk to me</h2>
      <p>
        email: <a href="mailto:hello@chuckreynolds.com" class="email">hello@chuckreynolds.com</a>
      </p>
